# Wave Function Collapse
Wave Function Collapse is a popular algorithm used for procedural generation in games. It is a step-based algorithm that generates each "chunk" one at a time, taking into account predetermined factors made by the designer.

## Example
1. To make things simpler, let's say we want to generate a world with:
    1. `Sand Tile`: Can be placed beside `Grass` & `Water`. Sand tiles can only exist in AT LEAST a 3x3 area.
    1. `Grass Tile`: Cannot be placed beside `Water`
    1. `Ocean Tile`: Cannot be placed beside `Grass`

1. Let's make the algorithm start at the top left of the world. Since it's the first tile it places, all 3 tiles has EQUAL probabilities to spawn.
    > And so the algorithm places an `Ocean Tile` on the first tile.\
    The grid looks like this:\
    ðŸŸ¦

1. Now, we move to the next tile horizontally. Since the tile was an `Ocean Tile`, the algorithm should know that it must not place a `Grass Tile` here. The probability to place a tile here is:
    1. `Sand Tile`: 50%
    1. `Grass Tile`: 0%
    1. `Ocean Tile`: 50%
    > The algorithm places a `Sand Tile` on the second tile.\
    The grid looks like this:\
    ðŸŸ¦ðŸŸ¨

1. Moving onto the next tile, since the rule for `Sand Tile` forces it to exist in a 3x3 grid, The probability to place a tile for this and the next tile is:
    1. `Sand Tile`: 100%
    1. `Grass Tile`: 0%
    1. `Ocean Tile`: 0%
    > And so the algorithm places a `Sand Tile` on the second and third tile.\
    The grid looks like this:\
    ðŸŸ¦ðŸŸ¨ðŸŸ¨ðŸŸ¨

1. Moving onto the next tile, since all the rules are adhered on this tile, all tiles have equal probability.
    > And so the algorithm places a `Grass Tile` on the fourth tile.\
    The grid looks like this:\
    ðŸŸ¦ðŸŸ¨ðŸŸ¨ðŸŸ¨ðŸŸ©

1. The algorithm will continue until the entire world is filled up, placing each tile one at a time.

## Implementation

1. We've made a simple Wave Function Collapse Map Generation to generate the levels of our game.

    ![](./images/wfc_image.png)

    General Settings (Map Data)
    * Chest Spawn \- stored data for chest types and different spawn chances.  
    * Map Size \- how many tiles wide and tall.  
    * Tile Size \- size of individual tile, change based on each chunk scale, for spacing purposes.  
    * Border Thickness \- how many layers of solid tiles go around the perimeter of the map, to prevent the camera from spilling over, showing the empty background.  
    * Map Seed \- input seed to get identical map generation every load, input â€˜0â€™ to get a randomized seed.

1. These are various tiles we have in our game, as well was their rules.

    ![][image1]

    [image1]: <data:image/png;base64,>

1. Example Chunks:
    1. Dead End Chunk\
    ![](./images/dead_end.png)
    1. Horizontal Chunk\
    ![](./images/horizontal.png)

1. Extra Settings (Map Objects). These will be instantiated after the map generation is completed.
    * Fog Prefab \- used for fog of war on the mini map.  
    * Door Prefab \- exit door to go to the next level.  
    * Portal Prefab \- used for fast travel around the map.

1. Map Generation Process:
    1. Place a random starting tile at a random space in the map.  

    2. Check adjacent tiles for tiles to â€˜collapseâ€™, and save them in a list.  

    3. Starts collapsing tiles from the list, beginning with the tile that has the least amount of possible tiles that it can be.  

    4. A marker moves to the collapsing tile, cross-checking all adjacent tiles, getting a random tile that satisfies the constraints of all adjacent tiles.  

    5. The new adjacent tiles are then added to the list of tiles to collapse, and the process from step 3 repeats, until the whole map has been collapsed and all the tiles are placed. 

    6. After the main map generation, the algorithm places a set amount of chests of random types around the map, up to a maximum amount.  

    7. Then, portals are placed around the map, to allow for easier traversal around the discovered areas of the map.  

    8. Finally, an exit door is placed in the furthest tile away from the player to ensure that the player has to play through the level to find the exit.

## Additional Information

* Since a tileâ€™s neighbor can be customized, it is possible to create a set of adjacent tiles that will always appear the same way by setting the constraints properly. E.g. 4 hallway tiles that can only be next to one another forming a repeatable hallway generation with those 4 tiles. This can also be used to make tiles with openings at different parts of the tile. These tiles would then be stored as Unique Tiles under the Map Data asset.  

* â€œSurfaceâ€ Levels are made possible as different naming conventions for the tiles allows the algorithm to be modified to place a certain named set of tiles differently.
